<!--HTML (index.html):
<!DOCTYPE html>: This declaration specifies that the document is an HTML5 document.

<html lang="en">: The <html> element is the root element of the HTML document, and lang="en" indicates that the document is in English.

<head>: The <head> section contains meta-information about the document, such as character encoding, viewport settings, and the title of the page.

<meta charset="UTF-8">: Specifies the character encoding as UTF-8, which is widely used and supports various characters and symbols.
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">: Sets the viewport configuration for responsive design on various devices.
<title>Your Static Website</title>: Sets the title of the webpage, which appears in the browser's title bar or tab.
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">: Links an external CSS file named "styles.css" to style the webpage. This allows you to separate the styling from the HTML for better organization.

<body>: The <body> element contains the main content of the webpage, including the header, sections, footer, and JavaScript link.

<header>: This section typically contains the website's title or logo and a navigation menu.

<nav>: Defines the navigation menu within the header.

<ul> and <li>: Create an unordered list for navigation links.

<section>: These are used to structure the main content of the page. In this template, there are sections for Home, About, Services, and Contact information. Each section has a unique id attribute, which can be used for creating internal links (e.g., <a href="#home">) to navigate to specific sections.

<footer>: Contains information that typically appears at the bottom of the webpage, such as copyright information.

<script src="script.js"></script>: Links an external JavaScript file named "script.js." JavaScript is used to add interactivity and dynamic behavior to the webpage.-->






<!--The CSS file (styles.css) contains the styling rules for the webpage, defining the colors, fonts, layout, and overall appearance of the website. It's referenced in the HTML using the <link> element.

You would define specific styles for elements like headers, navigation menus, sections, links, and the footer in this file-->



<!--The JavaScript file (script.js) is included at the bottom of the HTML body to ensure it runs after the HTML content has loaded. JavaScript is used to add interactivity to the webpage. 
    In this template, you can write JavaScript functions to handle things like form validation, animations, or any other dynamic features you want to implement on your website.You can create more complex scripts as needed for your website. 
    That's the breakdown of the provided static website template. It serves as a starting point for building a basic static website. You can customize the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to suit your specific project requirements. -->